<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-186  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 186.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 2 1989 v3 n40 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agencies respond to virus threats.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), theNational Security Agency's National Computer Security Center(NCSC), and the Software Engineering Institute (SEI) atCarnegie-Mellon University issued a statement that said no onecomputer virus poses a serious threat to the nation's computernetworks, despite rumors that one virus was set to go off on Oct12, 1989.andP;  NIST has established a computer-security resourcecenter to help computer users to protect their systems from thethreat of rogue programs.andP;  The center will also maintaininformation on viruses and other subjects related to computersecurity.andP;  Safe practices recommended by NIST include makingfrequent backups, buying software from reliable sources, andrestricting use of the computer to authorized users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesPreventive MaintenanceGuidelinesSecurity SystemsUnited States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologySabotage.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>